div.div:
The set of these interface structure/function structure connections can sometimes create a useful 'dead-end' which creates a certainty (creates a 'determined structure' from input info), such as 'after this point, one of these possibilities is guaranteed/determined to be true'.
Even more useful is the type of 'dead-end' that leads to high info-containing structures like 'types' or 'averages'.
The network of structures leading to these dead-ends is useful to identify.
These are different from similarity indexes (which unite functions by some similarity like similar rank) but can use similarity indexes like they can use other interface structures.
